---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Data Collection & Visualization in the Park | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="Meet for coffee, gather data by hand in the park, then come back and visualize it together."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: Data Collection &amp; Visualization in the Park
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Aug 29 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Meet at The Coffee Shop NE</span
                        ><br />2852 Johnson St NE · Minneapolis, MN</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                The best dataset is the one you gather yourself.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a morning that
                starts with coffee and ends with a chart. We'll meet at The Coffee
                Shop NE, walk over to Audubon Park to collect data by hand, then come
                back and turn what we gathered into a visualization.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Data collection is usually invisible — by the time most of us
                see a dataset, someone else has already decided what counts.
                This is a chance to make those decisions yourself: what to
                measure, how to tally it, and what gets left out. The
                constraints of a clipboard and forty minutes turn out to be the
                whole lesson.
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12 mb-8">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <img
                        src="/images/park-dandelions.jpeg"
                        alt="A field at Audubon Park dense with dandelion seed heads going to white"
                        class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                    />
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                How the morning will flow
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Coffee &amp; plan.</span
                        > Meet at The Coffee Shop NE for quick intros and to decide
                        what each of us will count.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Collect.</span
                        > Walk to Audubon Park and spend about forty minutes gathering
                        data — tallies, timings, sketches, observations.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Visualize.</span
                        > Head back and turn your raw tallies into something readable
                        — on paper, in code, or in beads and thread.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Share.</span> Compare
                        what we made — and how differently we each saw the same park.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Things you could count
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Pick one and go deep, or track a few at once. A handful of
                ideas:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Birds, squirrels, and dogs — by count, by type, by
                        minute</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >How people pass through: walking, running, biking,
                        rolling, with strollers</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Trees by species, or the colors of the leaves</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Dandelions in the grass — where they cluster and where
                        they don't</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Sounds — and how often each one interrupts the quiet</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Benches: how long anyone stays, and what brings them
                        there</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What to bring
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Something to record with — a notebook or your phone — and shoes
                for a short walk. A laptop is welcome for the visualizing part
                but not required; we'll have paper and making supplies on hand.
                Dress for the weather.
            </p>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Rain plan: light rain, we'll go anyway. Heavy rain, we'll
                collect our data right from The Coffee Shop NE.
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12 mb-8">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <img
                        src="/images/park-mushroom.jpeg"
                        alt="A single white mushroom growing among the grass and clover"
                        class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                    />
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone curious about where data comes from — practitioners and
                first-timers alike. No tools or experience required, just a
                willingness to notice things.
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                Hope to see you there!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
